               <div class="text-muted" style="font-size: 20px; margin-top: 16px;">   
                   To ensure fairness and professionalism, the 3rd Ottawa Youth Chinese Zodiac Painting Competition includes both Professional Group and Amateur Group categories. The following answers address common questions from parents and participants:
               </div>
               
               <div class="row" style="margin: 10px 0 10px 0;">              
	                <div class="col-md-6 col-sm-6 col-xs-12">
	                    <h3><b>Q1: What are the Professional Group and Amateur Group?</b></h3>
	                    <div class="text-muted">
							<div class="text-muted" style="font-size: 18px;">
Professional Group<br/>
The Professional Group is for young artists who have received systematic art training, including but not limited to:<br/>
- Long-term study in an art studio, art school, or workshop<br/>
- Training in sketching, color, composition, and creative practice<br/>
- A relatively solid art foundation and mature expressive ability.<br/><br/>
Amateur Group<br/>
The Amateur Group is for young artists who paint mainly out of interest and self-expression, including but not limited to:<br/>
- Learning mainly through school art classes or family interest activities<br/>
- No systematic professional training<br/>
- Children at an interest-development or foundational exploration stage
	                        </div>
	                    </div>        
	                </div>  
	                <div class="col-md-6 col-sm-6 col-xs-12">
	                    <h3><b>Q2: Why are there separate groups?</b></h3>
	                    <div class="text-muted">
							<div class="text-muted" style="font-size: 18px;">
The purpose of having Professional and Amateur Groups is to:<br/><br/>
 - Protect fairness<br/>
 - Respect different learning backgrounds<br/>
 - Establish reasonable judging standards<br/>
 - Encourage more children to participate in creative work<br/>
- Give each child a platform among peers at a similar level<br/><br/>

Without grouping, children with long-term professional training would compete directly with beginners, which would be less fair and could affect beginners' confidence.
	                        </div>
	                    </div>        
	                </div>        
	            </div>  
	            
	            <div class="row" style="margin: 10px 0 10px 0;">              
	                <div class="col-md-6 col-sm-6 col-xs-12">
	                    <h3><b>Q3: Is the Professional Group “higher” and the Amateur Group “lower”?</b></h3>
	                    <div class="text-muted">
							<div class="text-muted" style="font-size: 18px;">
Absolutely not.<br/>
"Professional" and "Amateur" only describe different learning backgrounds. They do not define ability, value, or potential.<br/>
Every child:<br/>
- Is growing<br/>
- Starts from a different point<br/>
- Progresses at a different pace<br/>
- Has a unique style<br/><br/>
Grouping is for fairer comparison, not for ranking children by worth.
	                        </div>
	                    </div>        
	                </div>  
	                <div class="col-md-6 col-sm-6 col-xs-12">
	                    <h3><b>Q4: Can participants choose their own group?</b></h3>
	                    <div class="text-muted">
							<div class="text-muted" style="font-size: 18px;">
Participants may register for the group that best matches their actual background.<br/><br/>
To maintain fairness, the organizing committee reserves the right to make reasonable group adjustments based on the submitted work and registration information when necessary.
	                        </div>
	                    </div>        
	                </div>        
	            </div> 
	            
	            <div class="row" style="margin: 10px 0 1px 0;">              
	                <div class="col-md-6 col-sm-6 col-xs-12">
	                    <h3><b>Q5: What matters most in the competition?</b></h3>
	                    <div class="text-muted">
							<div class="text-muted" style="font-size: 18px;">
Not the ranking, but:<br/>
- The creative process<br/>
- The courage to express oneself<br/>
- Growth in aesthetic awareness<br/>
- Building confidence<br/><br/>
For questions, please contact the competition committee at office@ocls-ottawa.ca. 
	                        </div>
	                    </div>        
	                </div>  
	                <div class="col-md-6 col-sm-6 col-xs-12">
	                    <h3><b>Our Purpose</b></h3>
